\u2192 retina","Cornea \u2192 aqueous humour \u2192 lens \u2192 vitreous humour \u2192 retina","Cornea \u2192 vitreous humour \u2192 lens \u2192 aqueous humour \u2192 retina","Lens \u2192 cornea \u2192 aqueous humour \u2192 vitreous humour \u2192 retina"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELight entering the eye follows a specific path through transparent structures. The correct sequence is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecornea \u2192 aqueous humour \u2192 lens \u2192 vitreous humour \u2192 retina\u003C/strong\u003E. Each structure plays a crucial role in focusing light and maintaining the eye\u0027s shape.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect pathways can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELens \u2192 aqueous humour \u2192 cornea \u2192 vitreous humour \u2192 retina\u003C/strong\u003E - This sequence is anatomically impossible as the cornea must be the first structure light encounters when entering the eye.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECornea \u2192 lens \u2192 vitreous humour \u2192 aqueous humour \u2192 retina\u003C/strong\u003E - The aqueous humour is located in the anterior chamber between the cornea and lens, not after the vitreous humour.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECornea \u2192 vitreous humour \u2192 lens \u2192 aqueous humour \u2192 retina\u003C/strong\u003E - The vitreous humour is located behind the lens, not between the cornea and lens.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELens \u2192 cornea \u2192 aqueous humour \u2192 vitreous humour \u2192 retina\u003C/strong\u003E - The cornea is the most anterior structure of the eye and must be encountered first.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cornea provides about two-thirds of the eye\u0027s focusing power, while the lens provides the remaining one-third and allows for accommodation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Light enters the eye through the cornea and is focused by both the cornea and lens onto the retina.","The cornea provides approximately two-thirds of the eye\u0027s refractive power, while the lens provides one-third.","Light must pass through multiple transparent structures before reaching the photoreceptors in the retina."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58209"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17704"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58209"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T07:46:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T07:46:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10418"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72739"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description